var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"api/#API","page":"API","text":"The complete reference for the exported functions, grouped by topic. CIKs are the SEC Central Index Key, zero-padded to 10 digits (Apple → 0000320193).","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Filings","page":"API","text":"List a filer's submissions, download filings, and turn them into text.","title":"Filings"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Financial-data","page":"API","text":"XBRL facts from the data.sec.gov structured-data endpoints.","title":"Financial data"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Full-text-search","page":"API","text":"Search the contents of filings (2001 onward) via the EDGAR full-text search API.","title":"Full-text search"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Company-lookup","page":"API","text":"Resolve ticker symbols to CIK numbers.","title":"Company lookup"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Configuration-and-caching","page":"API","text":"Responses are cached so an interactive session does not hammer the SEC. The SEC asks for fair use (no more than 10 requests per second), and a few endpoints return large payloads that get hit repeatedly: company_tickers.json is ~1 MB and cik_for_ticker consults it on every lookup, and company_facts can be several MB. Caching these avoids re-downloading them.\n\nThe cache is controlled entirely through set_config:\n\ncache = :temporary (default) — an ephemeral per-process temporary directory, deleted when Julia exits, so nothing persists or accumulates.\ncache = :persistent — kept in ~/.cache/EDGAR.jl across sessions; files older than cache_max_age (default 7 days) are pruned automatically.\ncache = :off — no caching; every call re-fetches.\n\nTwo independent time limits apply: cache_ttl (default 24 h) is freshness — how long a cached response is reused before being re-fetched — while cache_max_age governs how long a file lives on disk in persistent storage. Use clean_cache to prune on demand and cache_metrics to inspect hit/miss counts.","title":"Configuration and caching"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Command-line-entry-point","page":"API","text":"","title":"Command-line entry point"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.list_recent_filings","page":"API","text":"list_recent_filings(cik; count=10) -> Vector{NamedTuple}\n\nReturn a filer's most recent filings as up to count rows of (accession, form, date), newest first. Built on fetch_submissions.\n\nfor f in list_recent_filings(\"0000320193\"; count = 5)\n    println(f.date, \"  \", f.form, \"  \", f.accession)\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.list_recent_filings"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.fetch_submissions","page":"API","text":"fetch_submissions(cik) -> JSON3.Object\n\nFetch a filer's complete submissions document from data.sec.gov/submissions/: company metadata plus its recent filings index. cik should be the 10-digit, zero-padded Central Index Key (e.g. \"0000320193\"). See list_recent_filings for a tidied view of just the recent filings.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.fetch_submissions"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.download_filing","page":"API","text":"download_filing(cik, accession; primary=true, destdir=\".\") -> String\n\nDownload a filing's document from the EDGAR Archives into destdir, creating the directory if needed, and return the local file path. The accession number may be given with or without dashes. Several common document/index URL patterns are tried in turn; the first that responds with HTTP 200 is saved. Throws if none of them succeed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.download_filing"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.parse_filing","page":"API","text":"parse_filing(path) -> String\n\nRead a downloaded filing from path and return its raw HTML. The extraction functions (such as extract_section) operate directly on this HTML.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.parse_filing"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.extract_section","page":"API","text":"extract_section(html, names; max_chars=200_000, base_path=nothing) -> Dict{String,String}\n\nPull one or more named sections out of a filing's html, returning a dictionary that maps each requested name to the matched text. Names that cannot be located are simply absent from the result, so look them up with get.\n\nMatching is heuristic and tried in order: the document's table of contents (following anchor links), then DOM headings (h1–h6, via Gumbo + Cascadia), then a plain-text search as a last resort. base_path lets table-of-contents links that point to sibling files be resolved relative to it; max_chars bounds the size of the plain-text fallback window.\n\nsections = extract_section(html, [\"Item 7\", \"Management's Discussion\"])\nprintln(get(sections, \"Item 7\", \"(not found)\"))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.extract_section"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.save_filing","page":"API","text":"save_filing(text, metadata; outdir=\"out\") -> String\n\nWrite text to <outdir>/<accession>.txt, taking the accession number from metadata[:accession] and creating outdir if needed. Returns the path written.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.save_filing"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.company_facts","page":"API","text":"company_facts(cik) -> JSON3.Object\n\nEvery XBRL fact a company has ever reported, in a single document, from the /api/xbrl/companyfacts/ endpoint. cik is zero-padded to 10 digits.\n\nfacts = company_facts(\"320193\")\nkeys(facts.facts)              # taxonomies, e.g. :dei and Symbol(\"us-gaap\")\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.company_facts"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.company_concept","page":"API","text":"company_concept(cik, taxonomy, tag) -> JSON3.Object\n\nOne XBRL concept over time for a single filer, from /api/xbrl/companyconcept/.\n\nni = company_concept(\"320193\", \"us-gaap\", \"NetIncomeLoss\")\nni.units.USD[end].val\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.company_concept"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.xbrl_frames","page":"API","text":"xbrl_frames(taxonomy, tag, unit, period) -> JSON3.Object\n\nOne XBRL concept for one period across every filer that reported it, from /api/xbrl/frames/. A trailing I on the period denotes an instant (point in time, e.g. \"CY2022Q4I\"); drop it for a duration (e.g. \"CY2022\").\n\nfr = xbrl_frames(\"us-gaap\", \"Assets\", \"USD\", \"CY2022Q4I\")\nlength(fr.data)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.xbrl_frames"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.full_text_search","page":"API","text":"full_text_search(query; forms=nothing, startdate=nothing, enddate=nothing, from=0, size=10) -> JSON3.Object\n\nFull-text search across filing contents (2001 onward) via the EDGAR full-text search (EFTS) API. forms may be a single string (\"10-K\") or a collection; startdate/enddate are \"YYYY-MM-DD\" strings. Results are under .hits.hits.\n\nres = full_text_search(\"climate risk\"; forms = \"10-K\")\nres.hits.total.value\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.full_text_search"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.cik_for_ticker","page":"API","text":"cik_for_ticker(ticker) -> String or nothing\n\nResolve a ticker symbol (case-insensitive) to its 10-digit, zero-padded CIK, or nothing if no match is found.\n\ncik_for_ticker(\"AAPL\")     # \"0000320193\"\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.cik_for_ticker"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.company_tickers","page":"API","text":"company_tickers() -> JSON3.Object\n\nThe SEC's company_tickers.json, mapping ticker symbols to CIK numbers and company names.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.company_tickers"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.set_config","page":"API","text":"set_config(; cache, cache_dir, cache_ttl, cache_max_size, cache_max_age, host_whitelist, allow_file, user_agent) -> EDGARConfig\n\nOverride the global runtime configuration. Only the keyword arguments you pass (anything other than nothing) are changed; the rest keep their current values. Returns the live configuration object.\n\ncache — caching mode: :temporary (default; an ephemeral per-process temp directory that is wiped when Julia exits), :persistent (kept in ~/.cache/EDGAR.jl across sessions), or :off (no caching).\ncache_dir — pin a specific directory for the cache (implies persistent storage).\ncache_ttl — seconds a cached response stays fresh (controls re-fetching; independent of deletion).\ncache_max_size — largest response (bytes) that will be cached.\ncache_max_age — seconds a file is kept on disk before being deleted, in persistent storage. Pruning is on by default; this is a separate limit from cache_ttl and does not affect freshness.\nhost_whitelist — hosts that requests are restricted to (empty = no restriction).\nallow_file — whether file:// URLs are permitted (off by default; used in tests).\nuser_agent — the User-Agent header sent with every request. Set this to a descriptive value with contact information, as the SEC requires.\n\nset_config(user_agent = \"Jane Doe jane@example.com\", cache = :persistent)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.set_config"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.fetch_url","page":"API","text":"fetch_url(url; use_cache=true, timeout=15, allow_file=false) -> Vector{UInt8} or nothing\n\nLow-level cached HTTP GET. Sends the configured User-Agent (see set_config), returns the response body as bytes, and returns nothing on any failure (network error, non-200 status, or a disallowed URL).\n\nA successful response smaller than cache_max_size is written to the on-disk cache and reused for up to cache_ttl seconds. The cache mode set via set_config (:temporary, :persistent or :off) governs where it lives and whether it survives the process. In persistent storage, files older than cache_max_age are deleted automatically (independent of cache_ttl freshness); clean_cache also prunes on demand, and cache_metrics reports hit/miss counts. timeout is the read timeout in seconds. file:// URLs are only read when allow_file=true (for tests).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.fetch_url"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.clean_cache","page":"API","text":"clean_cache(max_age_seconds=CACHE_TTL) -> Int\n\nDelete cached responses whose stored timestamp is older than max_age_seconds, and return how many entries were removed. Corrupt cache entries are ignored.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.clean_cache"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.cache_metrics","page":"API","text":"cache_metrics() -> Dict\n\nReturn a snapshot (copy) of the cache counters: :hits, :misses, :requests and :bytes_downloaded.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.cache_metrics"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.cache_path_for","page":"API","text":"cache_path_for(url) -> String\n\nReturn the on-disk path (without extension) used to cache url. The actual cache files are this path with .body and .meta suffixes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.cache_path_for"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EDGAR.main","page":"API","text":"main(argv=ARGS)\n\nMinimal command-line entry point. Prints a hint pointing users at the module's functions; the package is intended to be used as a library rather than a CLI.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EDGAR.main"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#Examples","page":"Examples","text":"These examples assume you have set a User-Agent (see Home):\n\nusing EDGAR\nset_config(user_agent = \"Jane Doe jane@example.com\")","title":"Examples"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#Filings:-list,-download,-extract","page":"Examples","text":"# 1. List a company's recent filings by CIK (Apple = 320193)\nfilings = list_recent_filings(\"0000320193\"; count = 5)\nfor f in filings\n    println(f.date, \"  \", f.form, \"  \", f.accession)\nend\n\n# 2. Download the most recent filing's documents into a directory\nlatest = first(filings)\npath = download_filing(\"0000320193\", latest.accession; destdir = \"filings\")\n\n# 3. Read the filing's HTML (the extraction functions operate on HTML)\nhtml = parse_filing(path)\n\n# 4. Pull out specific sections (heuristic, case-insensitive)\nsections = extract_section(html, [\"Item 7\", \"Management's Discussion\"])\nprintln(get(sections, \"Item 7\", \"(not found)\"))","title":"Filings: list, download, extract"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#XBRL-financial-data","page":"Examples","text":"cik = cik_for_ticker(\"AAPL\")                  # \"0000320193\"\n\n# Every XBRL fact a company has reported, in one document\nfacts = company_facts(cik)\n\n# One concept over time (net income, in USD)\nni = company_concept(cik, \"us-gaap\", \"NetIncomeLoss\")\nprintln(ni.units.USD[end].val)\n\n# The same concept across every filer for one period\nassets = xbrl_frames(\"us-gaap\", \"Assets\", \"USD\", \"CY2022Q4I\")\nprintln(length(assets.data), \" filers reported Assets\")","title":"XBRL financial data"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#Full-text-search","page":"Examples","text":"hits = full_text_search(\"climate risk\"; forms = \"10-K\")\nprintln(hits.hits.total.value, \" matching filings\")","title":"Full-text search"},{"category":"section","location":"#EDGAR.jl-Manual","page":"Home","text":"Fetch company filings and financial data from the U.S. SEC EDGAR system, and pull out the parts you care about: a filer's submissions, filings downloaded and turned into text, named sections such as Item 7 — Management's Discussion, XBRL financial facts, and full-text search across filing contents.","title":"EDGAR.jl Manual"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Home","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(url = \"https://github.com/Trumpingtons/EDGAR.jl.git\")\n\nThis installs the package and its dependencies, including HTTP and JSON3 for talking to the SEC endpoints, and the Gumbo and Cascadia packages for robust HTML parsing. EDGAR.jl requires Julia 1.12 or later.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Set-a-User-Agent-first","page":"Home","text":"The SEC requires a descriptive User-Agent with contact information — requests without one are rejected with HTTP 403. Set yours once per session:\n\nusing EDGAR\nset_config(user_agent = \"Jane Doe jane@example.com\")","title":"Set a User-Agent first"},{"category":"section","location":"#A-first-look","page":"Home","text":"# Apple's Central Index Key is 320193 (zero-padded to 10 digits)\nfilings = list_recent_filings(\"0000320193\"; count = 5)\n\n# Net income over time, straight from XBRL\nni = company_concept(\"0000320193\", \"us-gaap\", \"NetIncomeLoss\")\n\n# Search the full text of 10-K filings\nhits = full_text_search(\"climate risk\"; forms = \"10-K\")\n\nSee Examples for worked, end-to-end usage and the API for the complete reference.","title":"A first look"}]
}
